author = {Ananya Banerjee},
keywords = {Blockchain, IoT-aided smart grid, Vulnerabilities, Smart contract, Public-private encryption, Peer to peer (P2P), Smart grid (SG)},
abstract = {Nowadays, blockchain, which is a revolutionary technology, is very much popular in business and enterprises such as energy trading, monitoring, maintenance, and organizational context. Most of them use this technology for its secure, cost-effective, and transparent features such as tamper-proof data structure, abolition of a third party, decentralized data management, data tracking, data integrity, authentication, authorization, transparent data exchange, etc. IoT-aided smart grids suffer from many vulnerabilities such as hacking and malicious attacks on grids, attacks on authenticity and authorization, insecure payment schemes, and no compliance monitoring. Blockchain technology solves some vulnerabilities, i.e., authentication can be done by public-private encryption with key access, which restricts the anonymous entry of intruders. All the transactions are recorded in an immutable format and decentralization makes the data exchanges transparent for all parties who are involved in this platform. This entire platform itself acts as a validator, which performs the transaction compliance monitoring and thus abolishes the third-party intervention and makes the system cost-efficient. Blockchain technology solves insecure payment vulnerabilities by creating wallets. In the case of energy trading, this technology performs a vital role to deploy the smart contracts, a negotiable software package code module to the underlying architecture, which controls the user access, validation for impure contracts, and thus provides the automation, transactional as well as contractual security. The main contribution of this work lies in a comparative study of IoT-aided smart grid management, control, and security, energy trading, payment schemes. This study shall help an end user to learn about how blockchain technology is the best fit for different use cases of IoT-aided smart grids.}
