abstract = {We live in a world of daily headlines of increasingly disastrous and impactful cyberattacks affecting governments, businesses, academic institutions, and healthcare professionals. It is estimated that global losses caused by cybercrime are now exceeding $1 trillion per year (McAfee Corp. New McAfee Report estimates global cybercrime losses to exceed $1 trillion, 2020) and are expected to continue to grow for the foreseeable future. From a cybersecurity perspective, diabetes care sits at an interesting crossroads. On one hand, diabetes devices are governed by the same respective national regulators (e.g., the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in the United States) as hospital-based medical equipment. On the other hand, they are used directly by the patient as part of their daily routine and increasingly in interaction with the patient's technology environment (e.g., their smart devices or local home networks). It is understandable that users of life-sustaining health technology, like the medical devices used in diabetes care, will ask whether their devices, and therefore their personal safety, may be at risk to a cybercompromise. This section will help to provide an understanding of the current state of cybersecurity in the diabetes ecosystem and will provide a balanced discussion of the topic so that the reader can make an educated decision about the potential cyberrisks versus the medical benefits provided by technology.}
